<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910320-0054</DOCNO><DOCID>910320-0054.</DOCID><HL>   Harris Unit Cleared   In Corruption Case</HL><DATE>03/20/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   HRS</CO><IN>COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   MELBOURNE, Fla. -- Harris Corp. said a federal judge inSan Francisco cleared the company's Digital Telephone Systemsdivision and two of its employees of any wrongdoing under theU.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act.   The electronics concern said District Judge Charles A.Legge, after hearing the prosecution's case, granted anacquittal. Harris said the defense wasn't called upon topresent its case.</LP><TEXT>   In August 1990, the division was charged with authorizingpayments to Colombian officials to influence the award of atelephone equipment contract. The division's general managerand director of human resources also were indicted.   Harris said no payments were made either directly orindirectly to any public officials. The company also saidthere was never any intention of making an improper payment,nor was one ever authorized or offered. Moreover, Harris saidit didn't even bid for the contract in question, and nocontract was awarded to the company.</TEXT></DOC>